Coming here from PR triage: it seems this is waiting for review by @urkud.
@AlexKontorovich In the mean time, can you merge master, please? Reviewing code which applies to current mathlib is always nicer... Thanks!

To show existence of primitives on balls, is seems that using `Complex.hasSum_taylorSeries_on_ball` and constructing a formal primitive of the Taylor series would be quicker than going through Morera (the way I learned it went through Morera -> holomorphic functions are C1 -> Cauchy formula -> everything else, the first step of which is matches this PR, but that feels a little like reinventing things that are in Mathlib already).

OTOH I know that rectangle integration is fundamental in PNT+ so it makes sense to have API for it in Mathlib.

> To show existence of primitives on balls, is seems that using `Complex.hasSum_taylorSeries_on_ball` and constructing a formal primitive of the Taylor series would be quicker than going through Morera (the way I learned it went through Morera -> holomorphic functions are C1 -> Cauchy formula -> everything else, the first step of which is matches this PR, but that feels a little like reinventing things that are in Mathlib already).

Yeah, that's a good point. I'm happy to abandon this approach entirely and switch to Taylor series. (This was a good warmup for understanding how to do PNT, but may no longer be necessary, having served its purpose...)

> OTOH I know that rectangle integration is fundamental in PNT+ so it makes sense to have API for it in Mathlib.

I wouldn't say that it's "fundamental" (in theory, we should eventually have the Jordan curve theorem, and be able to work more like the natural language proof...), but certainly it's proved useful to move things along...

> I wouldn't say that it's "fundamental" (in theory, we should eventually have the Jordan curve theorem, and be able to work more like the natural language proof...), but certainly it's proved useful to move things along...

Sure, let's say essential to the current proof then :-)

I wonder if this should be given a name reflecting its content, rather than its discoverer? This is the general mathlib convention – e.g., to pick a random example, the Hahn-Banach theorem is called `exists_extension_norm_eq`, not `hahn_banach_theorem`.

```suggestion
theorem VanishesOnRectanglesInDisc.hasPrimitive {c : ℂ} {r : ℝ} {f : ℂ → ℂ} (f_cont : ContinuousOn f (ball c r))

* `VanishesOnRectanglesInDisc.hasPrimitive`: **Moreira's Theorem**: A function which is 
  continuous on a disc and whose integral on rectangles in the disc vanishes has a primitive
  on the disc (defined by the wedge integral).
```
